1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
Hello, I'm Douglas Murray and welcome to Uncancelled History.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Today, colonialism.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:11,000
I'm joined by Professor Bruce Gilley.

4
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:17,000
Bruce Gilley is Professor of Political Science at Portland State University.

5
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:22,000
His research focuses on topics including colonialism and Asian politics.

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,000
In 2018, he published an article, The Case for Colonialism,

7
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:29,000
which was first published in the Third World Quarterly.

8
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
It sparked enormous protests and nearly half of the journal's editorial board

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,000
resigned in protest.

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:42,000
The author of numerous articles and books, in 2021,

11
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Gilley published his biography of Sir Alan Burns,

12
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:49,000
a 20th century British colonial officer.

13
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Today on Uncancelled History, Colonialism.

14
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:04,000
The Case for Colonialism

15
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:07,000
First of all, thank you so much, Bruce, for joining me.

16
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:12,000
In recent years, colonialism has been shown to be portrayed as

17
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,000
one of the absolutely foundational sins of the West,

18
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,000
perhaps along with slavery, racism.

19
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:23,000
Colonialism is one that has been most zoomed in on.

20
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:26,000
What is colonialism, first of all?

21
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:31,000
Well, I think if we take the biggest view, colonialism or imperialism,

22
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:34,000
as it used to be called before that became a dirty word too,

23
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:40,000
is simply where one group of people with an established form of government

24
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:46,000
travels to a part of the world where their government doesn't currently rule

25
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:48,000
and establishes its rule there.

26
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:54,000
And by that definition, all of world history is a history of imperialism and colonialism.

27
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:59,000
There is no people or no country today that has not at some point

28
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:02,000
been involved in imperialism and colonialism.

29
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,000
So nothing specifically unique or different about Europeans

30
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:08,000
doing exactly what everyone else did.

31
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,000
When people hear the term colonialism now,

32
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:19,000
they zoom in on a very specific and small portion of the world of colonialism,

33
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:24,000
which is basically 19th century and early 20th century European colonialism

34
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,000
in what we now call the Third World.

35
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Certainly in modern academia and perhaps the wider culture,

36
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:35,000
18th and 19th century European colonialism is now seen as being a sort of shorthand

37
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:41,000
for something that is unadulteratedly cruel, entirely racist.

38
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:45,000
What about this analysis in your view, full short?

39
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Well, in part because it's either true by definition or it's patently false.

40
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:57,000
True by definition because every group, up until very recently,

41
00:02:57,000 --> 00:02:59,000
was inherently racist towards other groups.

42
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,000
The Cherokees of the Americas were racist towards other Native Americans.

43
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:08,000
The Bantu were racist towards all of the Black African tribes they conquered

44
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,000
as they imperialized Southern Africa.

45
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:15,000
The Maori were racist towards other Pacific Asian tribes.

46
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:20,000
I mean, everyone was a racist if by that term we mean the assumptions by group A

47
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:26,000
that the members of group B are inferior and deserve to be conquered if they can be.

48
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:30,000
That's a universal human phenomena and it arises from evolutionary needs

49
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:32,000
for basically in group solidarity.

50
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:37,000
So racism is the standard default position for all peoples.

51
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:41,000
So to say that the Europeans were racist is just to state the obvious

52
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,000
because all peoples were racist.

53
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000
If it's not a statement of the obvious then it's patently false

54
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:52,000
and by that I mean that if we were to judge the racism of the Europeans

55
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:57,000
vis-a-vis the places they conquered, compared to the racism of other groups at the time

56
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,000
we would find the Europeans much less racist

57
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:03,000
and if we were going to put it on a spectrum we would say the only anti-racists

58
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
in the whole world at the time of European colonials and we're the Europeans

59
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,000
because they were the ones who went abroad and said these peoples have the capacity

60
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:12,000
to be just like us.

61
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
These people deserve freedom.

62
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
These people deserve to be freed from slavery.

63
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
They deserve to be developed.

64
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:22,000
They deserve to be civilized, which of course is seen as a sort of great racist act

65
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:23,000
but it's quite the opposite.

66
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
It's the act of saying all peoples have the potential to be self-governing,

67
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:31,000
to be flourishing, to have a written language, history, arts and culture.

68
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:36,000
This was the great anti-racist campaign that European colonialism represented.

69
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:41,000
So that's why I say it's either simply a statement of the obvious or it's patently false.

70
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:44,000
Roughly, what were other people at the time thinking?

71
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:49,000
You mentioned these were attitudes that Europeans held

72
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:54,000
but what would have been more normal attitudes at the time for the rest of the world about other groups?

73
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Well, the rest of the world, and this is true well into the 20th century,

74
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:08,000
basically that different groups saw themselves based on their ability to spread their rule

75
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:11,000
and their culture and their institutions to others

76
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:14,000
and they were more superior the more they were able to do that.

77
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:22,000
So this is why the Bantu expansion into southern Africa, the Buganda expansion throughout East Africa,

78
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:28,000
the Fulani Slave Empire of West Africa, all of these groups saw themselves as inferior

79
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:33,000
and saw those they conquered as not just moral inferiors but somehow subhuman.

80
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:39,000
In the sense that they weren't engaged in a civilizing action, they were engaged in a simple conquest.

81
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:48,000
And this was real racism in the sense of denying the humanity of those who were put under the subjugation

82
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:54,000
which is why these empires often were slave empires or simply genocidal empires.

83
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:56,000
The Europeans were different, right?

84
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:02,000
Not entirely, they had their brutal aspects, they had their old imperialist conquest aspects

85
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:08,000
but the seed of the difference in the European case was this idea of civilization.

86
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:13,000
Civilization raises those that you conquer from the level of subhuman to being human

87
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:16,000
because why would you civilize farm animals?

88
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
You civilize people who you tick to be your moral equals.

89
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:23,000
Now in 2017 you caused something of an uproar.

90
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:29,000
You wrote a piece called The Case for Colonialism in which you made the claim that European colonialism

91
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:32,000
was indeed beneficial to colonized people.

92
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:35,000
Can you tell us something about the backlash of attacks?

93
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:39,000
What you said in that article, what happened as a result of it?

94
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:44,000
Because this was a proper firestorm in your area.

95
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:49,000
This was, I wrote the article of 2017, The Case for Colonialism

96
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:53,000
because I was starting work on my biography of Sir Alan Burns,

97
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:57,000
great British colonial administrator which became the last imperialist

98
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:03,000
and I was trying to frame the basic case for colonialism that his life represented and he articulated.

99
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:08,000
And it went through peer review, got a split decision, the editor decided to run it,

100
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:13,000
kind of thinking it might be a good debate and literally within minutes of it appearing online

101
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:19,000
there were two online petitions started, one by a interpretive dance instructor in Britain

102
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:27,000
and one by an English professor in Manitoba and a third by a professor in Syracuse University

103
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:29,000
who also wanted my PhD revoked.

104
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:36,000
So three petitions actually which eventually had about 30,000 signatures demanding the article be retracted,

105
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:42,000
saying that this was violence against brown and black people, saying that this was holocaust denial,

106
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:48,000
saying that this was a threat to the safety of my students.

107
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:54,000
So my university launched a diversity investigation claiming my article was an act of violence.

108
00:07:54,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Eventually the editorial staff in London had death threats from nationalists in India.

109
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:03,000
They asked me could they please withdraw the article.

110
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:08,000
I said of course, not a big deal to me, their safety was paramount.

111
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:13,000
It was reprinted in Academic Questions which is the House Journal of the National Association of Scholars.

112
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:19,000
And I think thanks to the firestorm has attracted far more attention than it would have attracted

113
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:22,000
if it had simply been allowed to be read and disputed.

114
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:29,000
The original journal that it was published in then unpublished in just decided to pretend it hadn't happened?

115
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,000
So this is the third world quarterly.

116
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:34,000
No, they did things by the book.

117
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:41,000
They were not allowed to retract an article because of a political firestorm according to the ethics commission of the UK,

118
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:45,000
which actually is stronger than the ethics commission in the US for publishing.

119
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:52,000
So they had to ask my request to withdraw it, not retract it, which I agreed to for their physical safety.

120
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
So it was withdrawn, not retracted.

121
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:59,000
So if you go to the website today, you'll see the withdrawal notice that states very clearly that they faced death threats.

122
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:07,000
And the funny thing is now the third world quarterly has allowed, now that all their editorial staff has been revamped with ultra woke academics,

123
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:12,000
they're allowing their authors to cite the article again, but they're only citing the withdrawal notice.

124
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:20,000
They're not citing the actual article, but they're trying to kind of piggyback on the popularity of the article to generate metrics for their journal,

125
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:22,000
but you can't actually read the article on it.

126
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:27,000
So there are three petitions against you, including the interpretive dance lady.

127
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:32,000
And she didn't presumably make her objection through the form of interpretive dance, did she?

128
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:37,000
No, she used the method of a petition.

129
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:41,000
And you might say, well, okay, it's a free world.

130
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:42,000
And I do believe this.

131
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:47,000
I think if you want to set up a petition and oppose something, be my guest.

132
00:09:47,000 --> 00:10:02,000
But what was, I think, shocking to me was how many people signed that petition who were credentialed academics holding positions in universities in the UK and Canada and Australia and the United States,

133
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:07,000
universities which are by their very principles committed to the principle of academic freedom.

134
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:18,000
And so you have, I mean, okay, people signed petitions, but academics standing up very publicly and saying, I don't think this article deserves to be written.

135
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:21,000
I think academic freedom has certain limitations.

136
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:29,000
And when people say things that I think are racist or white supremacist, academic freedom has reached its limits.

137
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:35,000
It seemed to me that with that article, you had undoubtedly hit a tripwire in our day.

138
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:43,000
And the way I sort of thought of it in a way was perhaps there would have been a time maybe 100 years ago where to write, I mean, this isn't particularly the case,

139
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:51,000
but to write only negative things about colonialism and everybody involved in colonial projects would have caused some kind of problem.

140
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:59,000
And that what had happened is that in our own day, to say actually the picture is a bit more nuanced, more rounded, is just unacceptable.

141
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:09,000
It has to be that colonialism is like the Holocaust, as one of your accusers said, that it's just, there is no context, it's just bad.

142
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:11,000
Something like that, isn't it?

143
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:19,000
There's just a unanimity that there's no texture to be added that if somebody like you or Professor Nigel Bigger at Oxford says,

144
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:21,000
hang on, it's a bit more complicated.

145
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:25,000
Effectively, you're seen as being an apologist for the worst successes of colonialism.

146
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:37,000
So I actually think not because I think this idea that there was a time in European history or British history when it was nothing but daring,

147
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:42,000
to glorification of colonialism and the empire is a myth.

148
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:53,000
There was never a time in British history, in British education, in British newspapers where the imperial enterprise, where the colonies,

149
00:11:53,000 --> 00:12:01,000
whether we're talking the American colonies, Australia or later Africa, where this was not subject to a constant debate,

150
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:08,000
and where people who were critical of this were very free and very prolific in writing their criticism.

151
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:18,000
So I think this, you get this kind of, this narrative, especially in the UK that, well, at least we're not back in the days when it's all celebration of the empire.

152
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:24,000
And there was never a time in British history where there was nothing but glorification and celebration of empire.

153
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:26,000
Where do you think that idea comes from?

154
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:31,000
I think it's because the people think that they have a balanced perspective.

155
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:38,000
And by being balanced, they try to set up this idea that, well, I'm not like those crazy old imperialists like that all day.

156
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:39,000
I think we need balance.

157
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
And so I'm not on the right side of the spectrum.

158
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:43,000
I'm a centrist.

159
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:46,000
In fact, there was never that perspective.

160
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:49,000
So I think they're trying to make themselves feel like they're the centrists in the issue.

161
00:12:49,000 --> 00:13:00,000
Whereas, in fact, the arguments have always been about the critical and the contentious rollout of empire and what was happening.

162
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:13,000
And so anti-colonialism didn't arise in response to some excessively positive account of empire that was dominating and that was hegemonic in the empire.

163
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:14,000
It didn't, right?

164
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:15,000
Because that's its false flag.

165
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:18,000
It basically argues against a strawman, right?

166
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:19,000
There was never that.

167
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:25,000
And so what the anti-colonials are trying to do is to suggest that they're just bringing balance to the argument, right?

168
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:26,000
But they're not, right?

169
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:36,000
In fact, what they're doing is disbalancing the argument entirely, taking it from what it used to be, which is you could say the case for colonialism or the case against colonialism

170
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:40,000
and shut down the case for colonialism, say there's only one case to be made.

171
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,000
Anti-colonialism is the only case to be made.

172
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:55,000
And what you, Professor Nigel Bigger, a very small number of other academics have been doing is to be inserting this information into the debate, facts, interpretations of it,

173
00:13:55,000 --> 00:14:00,000
which seem just not to have been put in for a very long time, certainly not in the academic field.

174
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:03,000
So you mentioned, I mean, there are sort of positives about colonialism.

175
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:05,000
There are negatives.

176
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:13,000
What were the positives in your view for peoples in the countries that Europeans went to and ruled?

177
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:28,000
Well, I think we need to start at a very high level of abstraction because the fundamental thing is this, is if you were in a society which had a stone age level of technological development,

178
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:43,000
had no fixed borders, had no institutionalized system of governance, had not yet discovered the wheel, or in some more advanced places nonetheless still lived in an essentially feudal system, right,

179
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:50,000
with a very entrenched elite and a very impoverished population.

180
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:56,000
And you had the opportunity to be ruled by an advanced European civilization, right?

181
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:59,000
Why would you not want that to happen, right?

182
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:07,000
So just at the level of abstraction, like civilization A, which is superior to civilization B, and I have no problems using the term superior.

183
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:11,000
I'm going to say lots of people, the moment you say superior, they're going to...

184
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:12,000
Absolutely superior, right?

185
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:21,000
Because superior in the sense of better technology, better healthcare, better education, more accountable governance, more rights for marginalized communities,

186
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:32,000
especially women, urban development, technology, transportation, life-saving research and science, right?

187
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:33,000
Those are the things I mean.

188
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:34,000
This is superior, right?

189
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:39,000
And there's no objective definition, distinction between that and what's less.

190
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:42,000
If you had that opportunity, what would your society do?

191
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:49,000
Of course, they would jump at the opportunity, which is why so much of European imperialism spread with as much pull as it did push, right?

192
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:52,000
Indeed, the pull factors are often the dominating ones.

193
00:15:52,000 --> 00:16:01,000
The British went to Ghana, they said not much interested, left the Ghani kings, demanded that they come back, begged them to come back.

194
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:03,000
Finally, they did sign the treaties.

195
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:04,000
Why?

196
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:10,000
Because British Empire or other empires brought security, it brought stability, it brought opportunities.

197
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:19,000
It brought an end to inter-tribal warfare, which in many cases, these kings and these tribal leaders recognized was destroying their societies, right?

198
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:21,000
They needed essentially a hegemon.

199
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:24,000
I mean, it's an old Hobbesian story, but that's what they needed.

200
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:28,000
So, you know, at a very high level of abstraction, right?

201
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:35,000
I think that the onus of proof is that colonialism didn't bring tremendous benefits, right?

202
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:42,000
I mean, just in the sense of the logic of a more superior, I mean, you don't need to use superior, more developed, right?

203
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:48,000
More advanced civilization, having an opportunity to rule a less advanced civilization is so patently obvious, right?

204
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:55,000
That the burden of proof that this was not a good thing, I think lies upon those who say this somehow brought, bought harms.

205
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:02,000
And I think that's where we then have to get into, okay, so it's a good idea in general, right?

206
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:04,000
Was it a good idea in practice, right?

207
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:07,000
Now, this is where we need to talk about, like, how it rolled out.

208
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:11,000
Places were better, places were worse, there were abuses here, not here.

209
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:19,000
I mean, now we get into what used to be the debate on colonialism, which is let's talk about the practical opportunities, feasibility of things,

210
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:22,000
things that were done well, things were done badly in particular contexts.

211
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:27,000
But, you know, this idea of a blanket condemnation is just not tenable.

212
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:32,000
I suppose there's two things that the anti-colonialists say at this point, which is, first of all,

213
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:38,000
yes, there are maybe technical advances and so on, but that two things occur with colonialism.

214
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:44,000
One is the presumption that there are people who are sort of morally better, going into less morally developed societies.

215
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:51,000
And the other one would be something along the lines of you're instituting a form of inequality,

216
00:17:51,000 --> 00:18:00,000
and along the lines of that, along the way, you're also, for instance, eradicating local cultures, local norms.

217
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:03,000
Replacing local norms with European norms.

218
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:05,000
What do you say to those claims?

219
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:08,000
All of them don't withstand scrutiny.

220
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:17,000
Again, the idea of a moral superiority is one thing that was distinctly absent in the European mission.

221
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:27,000
If you take the idea of the civilizing mission seriously, what it implies is the moral potential of those who are colonizing to be exactly like you.

222
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:29,000
That's very explicit, right?

223
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:36,000
And in terms of life-saving medicines being morally superior to the absence of life-saving medicines,

224
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:39,000
yeah, I have no problems going to the mat and saying that's morally superior.

225
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:45,000
It's morally superior to save lives, to prevent people from being killed through violent conflicts,

226
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:48,000
to give rights to people who are traditionally marginalized.

227
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:49,000
That's morally superior.

228
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:50,000
I have no problem with that.

229
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:54,000
Most liberals would argue that, too, except when you talk about it in the context of colonialism.

230
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:58,000
Second of all, in terms of foreign norms or alien norms, don't forget,

231
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:02,000
almost all the places that were colonized were already under alien rule.

232
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:05,000
But it was indigenous alien rule, not European alien rule.

233
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:08,000
And we're talking mainly here about Africa.

234
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:15,000
Well, you know, most places, I mean, look at the Malay Peninsula, right?

235
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:22,000
I mean, basically, the Malay Peninsula was a bunch of small fiefdoms, small sultanates, right?

236
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:27,000
Those sultanates expanded or contracted based upon their power, right,

237
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:30,000
and brought in people who had been under another sultanate.

238
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:35,000
So, I mean, the idea of like indigenous rule, I mean, what is indigenous rule in a context

239
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:40,000
in which the world has always been organized by empire spreading as far as they can

240
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:44,000
and when they weaken being subjugated by other empires?

241
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:48,000
It is, you're right, most explicitly clear in Africa

242
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:52,000
because you can actually see what was happening at the time of European conquest.

243
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:56,000
I mean, the Fulani Slave Empire, which was basically an Islamic caliphate

244
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:03,000
of the central part of the Sahara, was spreading towards West Africa when the British came in.

245
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:08,000
The reason why it was so easy for the British to establish their control in northern Nigeria

246
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:15,000
was because those groups recognized the choice was British imperialism or the Fulani Slave Empire.

247
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:19,000
And the British Empire started to look very attractive compared to that.

248
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:22,000
Third point, destroying local cultures.

249
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:28,000
European imperialism was famous for its discovery and documentation and celebration of local cultures.

250
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:35,000
Many of these languages would not have survived, usually not the colonial administrators,

251
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:39,000
but the explorers and linguists and academics and researchers who came with imperialism

252
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:42,000
gone and documented those languages.

253
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:49,000
The U-language of Togo was essentially rescued by the Germans after they colonized it.

254
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:54,000
And there was two or three German linguists who went out and documented those languages

255
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:59,000
before they were lost, created dictionaries, created study guides.

256
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:03,000
I mean, the entire language would not exist but for German colonialism.

257
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:07,000
It's to say with James Princip and the language in India.

258
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:13,000
The British rediscovery of Indian heritage is well known.

259
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:20,000
I mean, I don't need to document it but the Asiatics and the Orientalists were the ones who rescued

260
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:26,000
and saved these cultures from destruction either by an indigenous empire or just by the forces of modernization.

261
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:30,000
Swihili was spreading in East Africa.

262
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:32,000
It was going to be the hegemonic language.

263
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:39,000
If the Germans had not documented those languages in the Mount Kilimanjaro area, those languages would have been lost.

264
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:43,000
There is a presumption, I think. We've come across it in a number of cases.

265
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:48,000
This presumption that if the Westerners, if the Europeans get it, go into a place,

266
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:53,000
they bring certain evils into an effectively Edenic society.

267
00:21:53,000 --> 00:22:01,000
The locals are otherwise living unbothered by modernity, by the vices of humankind.

268
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:05,000
Obviously, this wasn't the case.

269
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:11,000
But it seems that people are very reluctant to recognize that there's a balance of things going on here, at the very least.

270
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:18,000
Yeah, well, not only that the pre-colonial societies were not the Garden of Eden far from it

271
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:25,000
and had any of those pre-colonial societies been literate or had record-keeping traditions,

272
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:28,000
we would have more information on that. We don't.

273
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:33,000
So what do you turn to? You turn to the civilization that produced records and newspaper articles

274
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:39,000
and parliamentary inquiries and academic researches and whatnot, which is the European civilization.

275
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:44,000
The knowledge base is hugely biased towards the European colonial experience

276
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:49,000
and in particular, because it comes with a self-critical tradition, a lot of that knowledge is critical.

277
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:53,000
So this is somehow evidence that it was the Garden of Eden before European colonialism.

278
00:22:53,000 --> 00:23:00,000
It's clearly not the case. Secondly, quite aside from that, the more significant question is,

279
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:04,000
okay, if the Europeans had said, right, we're not going into Africa,

280
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:07,000
we're going to have this kind of agreement among ourselves not to go in.

281
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:08,000
So what would have happened?

282
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:13,000
Well, trade is still going to happen. Missionaries are still going to go in there.

283
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:19,000
Alcohol is going to go in there. The maximum machine gun is going to go in there.

284
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:28,000
So what you get then is a kind of Yahoo explorers and claim-stakers among the Europeans,

285
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:34,000
allying themselves with local forces. Would that have been a better governing experience for Africa?

286
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:42,000
So living in splendid isolation is not an option for Africa or the Middle East or Southeast Asia

287
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:45,000
or the Pacific at this time. Globalization is happening.

288
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:50,000
Do you want globalization to be governed or do you want it to be ungoverned?

289
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:55,000
And the ungoverned bits and pieces we have, such as the Congo Free State,

290
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:01,000
which actually was relatively well governed compared to some of the worst ones,

291
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:06,000
but the private colonies and Liberia under the Firestone Company

292
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:11,000
and some of the German trading companies in the Pacific,

293
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:15,000
obviously the East India Company before the Mutiny,

294
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:20,000
these private colonialism did not equip themselves very well.

295
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:25,000
So that's the alternative. The alternative is not splendid isolation.

296
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:30,000
The alternative is kind of these freelancers and mercenaries running these places,

297
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:33,000
which tended to be much worse because there was no accountability.

298
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:38,000
In 2020, you published your biography of Sir Alan Burns, The Last Imperialist.

299
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:42,000
First of all, before we get into the controversies around that,

300
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:47,000
perhaps you could explain who was Alan Burns and why was he somebody you wanted to write about?

301
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:52,000
Burns was a colonial administrator born in the Caribbean,

302
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:58,000
went to West Africa on the eve of World War I, fought in the West Africa campaigns in the Cameroons

303
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:03,000
and in Togo was then put on the Nigerian government,

304
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:09,000
became a colonial secretary in the Bahamas, became the governor of Belize,

305
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:13,000
or what was then the British Honduras, eventually became the governor of the Gold Coast,

306
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:15,000
which is now Ghana during World War II.

307
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:21,000
And then after that, a very kind of storied colonial career was sent to the United Nations

308
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:24,000
in the 50s to basically stand up for the British Empire

309
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:29,000
when the United Nations was becoming a kind of decolonization machine, right?

310
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:36,000
What interested me about Burns was he was an unapologetic defender of empire

311
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:38,000
way into the 20th century.

312
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:40,000
He dies in 1980.

313
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:46,000
Right, so he is one of the few people who carries on the case for colonialism

314
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:52,000
well after most British have kind of retired in a kind of awkward, cringy feeling about,

315
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:55,000
well, that wasn't very nice, but long as I have my pension,

316
00:25:55,000 --> 00:26:00,000
and of course the 60s is the era of the great radical anti-colonial movements,

317
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:04,000
not only in the global system, but on campus, of course,

318
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:07,000
and Burns is pushing the argument right to the end, right?

319
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:10,000
And presently enough, because he lives through the 70s,

320
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:13,000
which is the great lost decade in the developing world, right,

321
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:17,000
where massacres and wars and humanitarian catastrophes that we didn't notice

322
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:19,000
because there's no white men involved.

323
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:21,000
But I mean, this was the great lost decade of the Third World.

324
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:23,000
Where are we talking about here?

325
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:25,000
Oh, we're talking about all of Africa, essentially.

326
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:28,000
We're talking about Indonesia.

327
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:34,000
We're talking about the period of conflict in the Middle East.

328
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:40,000
We're talking about India itself, the great, like, granddaddy of them all, right,

329
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:46,000
with stagnation, with communal violence, with an emergency and a suspension of democracy.

330
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:50,000
Basically, every part of the Third World is falling apart

331
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:55,000
and going into spiral in the 70s, right, and it slowly starts to recover by the 80s.

332
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:58,000
But Burns is paying attention to this, right?

333
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:03,000
Burns is paying attention to the massacres, the Biafra war, right,

334
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:05,000
is maybe the one that draws world attention,

335
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:09,000
because we're talking one to two million people killed in that.

336
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:14,000
Of course, partition might have caused some misgivings

337
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:17,000
about this whole decolonization idea.

338
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:19,000
But Burns is kind of arguing the case.

339
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:21,000
This is why we shouldn't have ended it so fast.

340
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:26,000
This is why the United Nations mishandled this whole issue, right?

341
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:29,000
They were so obsessed with getting the colonialists out

342
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:32,000
that they didn't pay attention to what was going to take over

343
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:34,000
and who was going to fill the power vacuum

344
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:36,000
and were these going to be stable states?

345
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:40,000
So I wrote the biography because I found him a compelling figure.

346
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:42,000
I also tracked down his family.

347
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:46,000
I saw his papers sitting in an attic in Chelmsford.

348
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:48,000
And, you know, classic kind of British thing.

349
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:50,000
I mean, here's the guy who, in my mind,

350
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:55,000
is one of the greatest generation of the late colonial administrators

351
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:58,000
who are helping to get these countries ready for independence.

352
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:03,000
And he's just kind of treated with this icy coldness.

353
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:06,000
And there's his paper sitting in an attic in Chelmsford,

354
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:09,000
you know, because you wouldn't want to write about this person, right?

355
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:11,000
I mean, what an evil person this is.

356
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:13,000
And yet he is a great...

357
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:15,000
I mean, he's a hero of the British people, in my mind,

358
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:17,000
but the British were not interested in it.

359
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:19,000
By the way, before we come back to Bernadette,

360
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:22,000
one of the things that's always interested me about the post-colonial period

361
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:25,000
are the number of post-colonial writers who say

362
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:28,000
there is a form of Western colonialism that these countries,

363
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:31,000
particularly in Africa, have had to suffer under

364
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:34,000
and that they must be returned to another state.

365
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:37,000
Now, the obvious thing, it seems to me, is that you would argue

366
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:40,000
that they should be returned to some pre-colonial state.

367
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:42,000
But that argument seems to be quite uncommon.

368
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:46,000
A lot of the people I'm thinking of writers like Franz Fanon and others,

369
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:49,000
once the anti-colonialist movement gets going,

370
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:52,000
argue for Marxism for these societies.

371
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:57,000
In other words, they say Western imperialism has been the problem

372
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:00,000
and that we must therefore return these societies

373
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:04,000
and we must return them to Western Marxism.

374
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:06,000
And there was always something...

375
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:10,000
There was always something specifically political going on that era as well, wasn't it?

376
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:12,000
Because we're talking about the 60s,

377
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,000
we're talking about still dreams of Marxism going on,

378
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:18,000
and it seemed like the post-colonial developing world

379
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:23,000
could always be used as another experimenting place for that.

380
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:28,000
Right, so the great myth of anti-colonialism

381
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:31,000
is that it represented indigenous forces

382
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:34,000
and indigenous resistance to colonialism.

383
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:39,000
And it didn't. It represented European intellectuals

384
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:44,000
exporting their ideologies to hapless brown and black people

385
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:48,000
and finding people like Fanon or Amacal Cabral,

386
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:53,000
who spent most of their time hanging out in cafes in Paris and Lisbon,

387
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:56,000
and sending them back as representatives of the people,

388
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:00,000
oppressed black people who needed to lead the fight against colonialism.

389
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:02,000
But these people didn't represent anything in their societies.

390
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:03,000
They barely had traveled.

391
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:06,000
Most of them couldn't speak the languages of their own societies.

392
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:10,000
What they brought back was not some indigenous response to colonialism.

393
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:14,000
What they brought back was a bunch of half-assed ideologies from Europe.

394
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:21,000
Most of them Marxist or Leninist or vaguely post-modernist as Fanon was.

395
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:26,000
And what's interesting in terms of this decolonization process is

396
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:30,000
the indigenous leaders in these societies saw that, right?

397
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:32,000
They said to the Europeans,

398
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:35,000
don't you dare hand over power to these people, right?

399
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:41,000
This was the great king of the Congo who was saying to the Belgians,

400
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:45,000
this guy, Patrice Lumumba, is a madman, right?

401
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:48,000
Don't give in to them. Don't promise independence.

402
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:51,000
Don't hand over to these people because they're a bunch of loudmouths

403
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:53,000
and they're the minority, right?

404
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:56,000
We need you to stay, right? We're not ready for independence.

405
00:30:56,000 --> 00:31:00,000
Even Julius Nierere, who became the first prime minister of Tanzania

406
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:04,000
and then president of Tanzania, was very explicit when he went to the United Nations

407
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:09,000
and said, we're being pushed towards independence way faster than we'll be ready for it.

408
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:13,000
Julius Nierere didn't think Tanzania would be ready for independence

409
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:15,000
until about the year 2000, right?

410
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:19,000
But the momentum was, you have to resist colonialism.

411
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:21,000
You have to go.

412
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:26,000
And so these people who had no ability to hold these countries together

413
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:29,000
and were bringing in not some indigenous wisdom of governance,

414
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:33,000
but half-baked Marxist theories were thrown into power

415
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:36,000
as representatives of the people against European colonialism.

416
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:39,000
And this was because there was a perception of the winds of change.

417
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:42,000
There was just a historic moment. There was no point resisting it.

418
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:44,000
It's two things.

419
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:46,000
First of all, Europe is exhausted after World War II

420
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:51,000
and European populations are lining up for bread.

421
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:54,000
They have no heating. They have no electricity.

422
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:01,000
The appetite for providing global public goods to foreign peoples was at an end, right?

423
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:05,000
And one of the tragedies of World War I and World War II

424
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:10,000
was this loss of European willpower to maintain empires, right?

425
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:15,000
So first of all, there's no support for colonialism on the home front.

426
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:18,000
That's the most fundamental reason for the end of colonialism.

427
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:21,000
It's not Gandhi standing up to the British Empire,

428
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:25,000
you know, these virtuous George Washington's with black skin,

429
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:28,000
bringing down the pretensions of this strong imperialist.

430
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:30,000
No, nonsense.

431
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:33,000
The imperialists were brought down by the home front,

432
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:36,000
who said, we're done with colonialism.

433
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:38,000
We can barely feed our families, right?

434
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:41,000
And so the willpower on the home front evaporated.

435
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:44,000
Later on top of that, you now have the Soviet Union,

436
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:48,000
styling itself as the liberator of black and brown people everywhere,

437
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:52,000
even as it's colonizing Central Asia, Eastern Europe, the Baltics.

438
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:54,000
But anyways, put that aside, they're liberators,

439
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:57,000
and of course they'll bring democracy and prosperity everywhere they go.

440
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:02,000
Well, now at the United Nations, you have this dance of the Soviet Union and the United States.

441
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:06,000
The United States having its anti-colonial tradition,

442
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:09,000
but recognizing that this is not going to end well,

443
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:17,000
but not wanting to be outflanked by the Americans for the participation of these third world governments.

