00:49:10,000 --> 00:49:15,000
You know, don't really care that dropping large wads of cash into communities

667
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:20,000
is extremely harmful to their productive capacities, creates all kinds of malign impacts,

668
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:22,000
but they don't really care about that.

669
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:27,000
So the Germans dropped this big wad of cash on the Namibian government two years ago

670
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:29,000
saying that's it, now we're done, right?

671
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:31,000
Now we've atoned for our sins, right?

672
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:36,000
It sets off a mad scramble, as you suggest, among the cadres for who's going to get this money.

673
00:49:36,000 --> 00:49:38,000
It doesn't achieve anything.

674
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:43,000
That's the only form of reparations that actually works now,

675
00:49:43,000 --> 00:49:48,000
which is identifying a clear set of alleged victims in a particular incident, right,

676
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:51,000
in which a clear harm was supposedly made.

677
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:58,000
But the argument of reparations for colonialism itself, I mean, it's a non-starter as a moral question,

678
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:01,000
but it's also, I think, a non-starter as a practical question.

679
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:06,000
Now as we start to wrap up, first of all, is colonialism worth reclaiming?

680
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:14,000
What are the aspects of it that could be applied if understood properly in the world today?

681
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:19,000
Well, colonialism happens whether we like it or not

682
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:30,000
in the sense that dysfunctional governments have their governance capacities taken over by external actors.

683
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:36,000
Often it's an IMF loan with conditions, or it's a World Bank loan with conditions about governance.

684
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:38,000
You'd call that colonialism of a kind?

685
00:50:38,000 --> 00:50:41,000
It's not colonialism, but it's external governance.

686
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:50,000
And it draws much on colonial experiences in terms of how you can enhance indigenous capacity

687
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:55,000
by keeping some form of gatekeeping or tutelary role on the outside, right?

688
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:58,000
But that's how colonialism was trying to develop self-government, right,

689
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:04,000
which is as much indigenous native government as possible, creating structures,

690
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:08,000
allowing the governor to veto acts, allowing the governor to appoint the district commissioner.

691
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:13,000
I mean, that was the sort of what Lugard called the dual mandate, right,

692
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:18,000
and sort of our mandate to the local government and the local government's mandate to its people,

693
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:20,000
and that's how we're going to operate.

694
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:23,000
No, I don't like to use the word colonialism for that type of external governance,

695
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:25,000
because that's really just external governance, right?

696
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:28,000
Now there are opportunities for actual colonialism.

697
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:34,000
I mean, Paul Romer, who is the World Bank official economist, right,

698
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:38,000
a University of Chicago professor, proposed this idea of a charter city, right,

699
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:45,000
to take a piece of land in one of these countries, lease it from the government for a dollar a year, right,

700
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:49,000
and put it under the formal rule of an external power, right?

701
00:51:49,000 --> 00:51:52,000
So a charter city would be kind of like what Hong Kong was, right?

702
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:59,000
It's basically a leased piece of land that is put under the sovereignty of a western government for a fixed amount of time,

703
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:03,000
during which its laws and its rule apply there.

704
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:06,000
It's allowed to trade, people are allowed to migrate, right?

705
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:11,000
And what it does is it creates this little kind of dynamo of economic success

706
00:52:11,000 --> 00:52:16,000
along the coast or in the territory that eventually can be handed back.

707
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:23,000
I mean, Romer says that Hong Kong itself, given the number of people it positively affected in China,

708
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:27,000
because of its demonstration effects, because of how the Chinese learn from it,

709
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:32,000
can almost single-handedly be used to justify British colonialism just by the numbers, right?

710
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:38,000
Because if it's responsible for China's economic boom, then it's a pretty big data point.

711
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:40,000
So ideas like that.

712
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:44,000
Now, it's tough to bring in the white man, mainly because the white man doesn't want to be there, right,

713
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:46,000
because of the opposition.

714
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:50,000
But we do see, for example, non-white countries going in.

715
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:55,000
So the South Koreans have created essentially a small colony in Bangladesh.

716
00:52:55,000 --> 00:52:57,000
It's basically an industrial zone.

717
00:52:57,000 --> 00:53:00,000
It's run by the Korean Development Authority.

718
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:02,000
It's a walled city.

719
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:04,000
It's got factories.

720
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:05,000
It's got schools.

721
00:53:05,000 --> 00:53:07,000
It's got its own governments.

722
00:53:07,000 --> 00:53:09,000
It's basically a little Korean colony in Bangladesh.

723
00:53:09,000 --> 00:53:15,000
Nobody notices it because they're all like brown and yellow and aren't they all just the same?

724
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:18,000
And who cares about the Koreans colonizing Bangladesh?

725
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:19,000
I think it's great.

726
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:20,000
It's a model.

727
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:30,000
You've also seen some behavior like that in Yemen, in the north end of Yemen, where the Qataris and Saudis and the Turks

728
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:35,000
basically created a colony, a colony that's externally run.

729
00:53:35,000 --> 00:53:40,000
I think that that's a great model to follow because the Yemenis can't stand up their own government.

730
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:47,000
This is all kind of beyond the New York Times' horizon of interest because they're all brown and black people,

731
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:51,000
and there's no white man with a pith hat on to decry.

732
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:53,000
But it's actually working quite well.

733
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:56,000
And I think that type of colonialism has a lot of potential.

734
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:00,000
What about Chinese colonialism in Africa today?

735
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:02,000
Would you call that colonialism?

736
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:06,000
It's not even external governance for the most part because the Chinese,

737
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:11,000
unlike the South Koreans, don't actually have a governance model that they can share.

738
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:13,000
So the Chinese invest a lot.

739
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:15,000
Yeah, they create company towns.

740
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:19,000
They provide infrastructure, but they're not doing governance.

741
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:23,000
What's the difference in a town that you buy up and run?

742
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:28,000
Well, because the Chinese still are not bringing in their own administrators.

743
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:34,000
They're not setting up their own special zone laws the way that, say, the Koreans did in Bangladesh.

744
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:36,000
I mean, they're still relying on local police.

745
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:38,000
They're still using local laws.

746
00:54:38,000 --> 00:54:43,000
I mean, they're not really trying to govern beyond just running their enterprises.

747
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:47,000
Now, yeah, those enterprises are big, sprawling institutions,

748
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:50,000
but they're still just like one company operation.

749
00:54:50,000 --> 00:54:52,000
So I don't see the Chinese doing it.

750
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:55,000
The Chinese are smart enough to know that they can't do that, right?

751
00:54:55,000 --> 00:54:57,000
That they can't govern other peoples.

752
00:54:57,000 --> 00:54:59,000
Do they not want to?

753
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:01,000
I don't think they want to.

754
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:02,000
They want their money.

755
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:03,000
They want their investment.

756
00:55:03,000 --> 00:55:07,000
They want their leverage over those governments in terms of the economic leverage.

757
00:55:07,000 --> 00:55:13,000
But I don't think they see themselves as having an interest, even,

758
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:17,000
in spreading their governance model to other parts of the world.

759
00:55:17,000 --> 00:55:20,000
Indeed, their whole discourse is to each his own.

760
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:24,000
It's interesting that today when we talk about colonialism,

761
00:55:24,000 --> 00:55:28,000
countries like America, Israel, and others,

762
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:34,000
the term is used sometimes of them as a sort of smear or a slander.

763
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:39,000
Even there's nothing that America is doing that is colonial

764
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:42,000
by the terms that you've just laid out.

765
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:44,000
Yet, for some reason, it is still seen,

766
00:55:44,000 --> 00:55:49,000
what is seen today as something that only, as you say, white people would be guilty of

767
00:55:49,000 --> 00:55:51,000
or could be guilty of.

768
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:52,000
Is that true?

769
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:56,000
Yeah, it's trying to backcast the word to say any settlement

770
00:55:56,000 --> 00:55:59,000
or expansion of one's territory makes you colonial.

771
00:55:59,000 --> 00:56:05,000
So if that's the case, virtually all of the Native American tribes are colonial as well.

772
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:10,000
I mean, all of the lands claimed by the Cherokee are colonial takings from other tribes.

773
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:17,000
The Hawaiians who claim indigeneity in Hawaii arose from colonial processes

774
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:19,000
in the Hawaiian Islands and the South Pacific.

775
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:21,000
So we're all colonial.

776
00:56:21,000 --> 00:56:23,000
So it's just a statement of the obvious, right?

777
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:28,000
And to say that a place like Puerto Rico is colonial.

778
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:33,000
Well, of course, the Puerto Ricans have never demanded independence, right?

779
00:56:33,000 --> 00:56:36,000
I mean, the independence movement is a flop in Puerto Rico

780
00:56:36,000 --> 00:56:38,000
for reasons that they know well, right?

781
00:56:38,000 --> 00:56:39,000
Because it would be a disaster.

782
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:41,000
I mean, they benefit from that connection.

783
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:47,000
The little bits of colonies left around the world, the French pieces, the British pieces, right?

784
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:48,000
They have referendum.

785
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:53,000
There's a place that's related to the Norfolk Islands off New Zealand.

786
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:54,000
I mean, they have referendum.

787
00:56:54,000 --> 00:56:59,000
They never achieve a necessary majority because these places know how much they benefit

788
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:01,000
from that colonial connection.

789
00:57:01,000 --> 00:57:08,000
As we wrap up, I come back to where we started, the outrage, attempted cancellations of you

790
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:13,000
and a few other academics who actually investigate research in these areas

791
00:57:13,000 --> 00:57:18,000
without just coming to what seemed to be the preordained conclusions you're meant to come to.

792
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:22,000
And just to return to that, as I see it,

793
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:27,000
the criticisms that have come towards you, the criticisms that have come to others in the same area,

794
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:32,000
it's almost as if there's an area of the past on this occasion, colonialism,

795
00:57:32,000 --> 00:57:36,000
but there are others as well that's effectively behind crime scene tape,

796
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:38,000
and you're not meant to go there.

797
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:43,000
And as I see it, the reason that people don't want you to go there

798
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:48,000
is because they somehow think that if you do, we're going to do it again.

799
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:53,000
You heard that a certain amount in recent years in Britain.

800
00:57:53,000 --> 00:57:58,000
There were people who claimed that the Brexit vote was just the beginning of a new era

801
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:05,000
of British Empire building, and no member of the British government has at all expressed

802
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:09,000
an interest in going and taking over other parts of the world in the last six years,

803
00:58:09,000 --> 00:58:10,000
very far from it.

804
00:58:10,000 --> 00:58:15,000
They seem to be wanting to govern their own state as well or badly as they can,

805
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:20,000
but that seems to be a motif that has been emerging.

806
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:22,000
Don't deal with this stuff.

807
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:25,000
Don't even weigh up the pros and cons of colonialism,

808
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:31,000
because the moment you talk about the pros, we'll just be off again.

809
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:32,000
Do you agree?

810
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:36,000
Yeah, and I think it's even bigger than that.

811
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:41,000
I mean, it's true that they don't want to legitimate the idea of western control

812
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:45,000
or rule over any part of the world, even if people's in other parts of the world

813
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:49,000
would line up to be ruled by western countries.

814
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:51,000
I think that's true, by the way, separate issue.

815
00:58:51,000 --> 00:58:54,000
But I think there's a bigger issue here, and it's part of what your book,

816
00:58:54,000 --> 00:59:00,000
The War on the West, is about, which is that colonialism is seen as kind of unambiguous bad

817
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:04,000
that can be chalked up on the negative side of western society

818
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:08,000
and constantly used to bash it whenever it claims any right.

819
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:13,000
And part of it's a response to the fact that as the world progresses,

820
00:59:13,000 --> 00:59:16,000
the West is getting stronger, in my view.

821
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:17,000
It is getting stronger.

822
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:19,000
It is getting more dominant.

823
00:59:19,000 --> 00:59:21,000
It is getting more attractive.

824
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:24,000
The rivals are falling by the wayside.

825
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:27,000
The Chinese model is flat.

826
00:59:27,000 --> 00:59:28,000
The Russian model is over.

827
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:31,000
The Brazilian model is long dead.

828
00:59:31,000 --> 00:59:36,000
I mean, so I think there is this kind of resentment about the success of the West.

829
00:59:36,000 --> 00:59:40,000
And colonialism has become this kind of quiver of arrows.

830
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:44,000
Let's say, whenever you talk about the West, let's not forget colonialism.

831
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:49,000
And the requirement there is that that debate be not available for discussion.

832
00:59:49,000 --> 00:59:52,000
That that's just an unambiguous bad, and you're supposed to bow your head and say,

833
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:54,000
yes, you're right, that's a bad part of it.

834
00:59:54,000 --> 01:00:02,000
So they hate the idea that this box, this Pandora's box of debate could be opened

835
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:09,000
because it weakens what to them is one of their key kind of charges in opposition to the rise of the West.

836
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:12,000
Well, Professor Bruce Gilley, thank you very much.

837
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:16,000
We've covered an enormous amount of terrain, but that was absolutely fascinating

838
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:21,000
and has certainly given us a new view on an old question of colonialism.

839
01:00:21,000 --> 01:00:22,000
Thank you.

840
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:23,000
Thank you.

841
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:34,000
Thank you.

